  <h1 class="page-title">Finding My People<br>Thirty Years Later</h1>
  <p class="page-subtitle">An alumna's journey back to community</p>
</section>

<!-- ESSAY BODY -->
<section style="padding:72px 60px;background:white">
  <div style="max-width:680px;margin:0 auto">

    <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.25rem;line-height:1.75;color:#2C2C2C;margin-bottom:2rem;font-style:italic">
      I graduated in 1994. I did not attend a single alumni event for twenty-six years. Then someone sent me an email about the BAA.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      Here is what I remember about being Black at Denison in the early nineties: finding people. That was the project. Every time you walked into a room you did a quick scan — who here looks like me? Who here might understand what it's like to be called on to represent the entire race in a seminar on American history?
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      We found each other, of course. We always do. There was a group of us — not a formal organization, just a constellation of people who showed up for each other. We ate together, stayed up late together, argued about music and politics and what it meant to be at a school like this. Then we graduated and scattered.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.75rem;font-weight:500;margin:2.5rem 0 1rem;color:#2C2C2C">The Long Silence</h2>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      I am not sure why it took me so long to reconnect. Life happened — career, family, a move across the country. Denison felt like something in the past, a place I had survived and moved on from.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      But "survived" is the wrong word, actually. I thrived at Denison. I had extraordinary professors. I found a mentor in the English department who still sends me books. I made friendships that have lasted thirty years. What I didn't have was a relationship with the institution after I left. No one reached out. No one made it feel like my ongoing participation was wanted.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.75rem;font-weight:500;margin:2.5rem 0 1rem;color:#2C2C2C">What Changed</h2>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      The email was simple. Someone had restarted the BAA and wanted to know if I'd join a call. I almost didn't open it. I almost definitely didn't intend to respond. But something about seeing the name — Black Alumni Association — made me click.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      On that first call, I recognized a name from my graduating class. We had been in the same English seminar. We had not spoken since 1994. Within five minutes, we were laughing about a professor we'd both had, comparing notes on what our lives had looked like since, and talking about what we wanted to see the BAA become.
    </p>

    <div style="background:var(--cream,#F9F5EE);border-left:4px solid #078D70;padding:1.5rem 2rem;margin:2.5rem 0">
      <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.35rem;font-style:italic;line-height:1.5;color:#2C2C2C;margin:0">
        "The community was always there. We just needed someone to organize it."
      </p>
    </div>

    <p style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.85;color:#444;margin-bottom:1.5rem">
      That is the thing about Black Denison alumni: we are already connected, already invested, already proud. We just don't always have a structure that makes it easy to show up. The BAA is building that structure. And I, for one, am glad I finally opened the email.
    </p>

